The most common channel which diet affects cognition is by nutrient intake, and a variety of nutrients have been found to reduce the risk of cognitive impairment, such as polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFA), antioxidants, and B vitamins [30, 58, 59], and these nutrients may affect cognition through vascular or neural mechanisms or both [58]. For example, high intake of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega$$\end{document}ω-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFA) from fish or vegetable sources may reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease and possibly Alzheimer’s disease through vascular mechanisms [60], and may also play a significant protective role in the cellular mechanisms involved in neurodegeneration, thereby reducing the risk of poor cognition [30, 58]. Moreover, these nutrients that prevent cognitive decline are obtained during the intake of adequate components of whole grains, vegetables, fruits, soy, fish and seafood, eggs and seeds and nuts as part of the CHEI score [37, 42, 43].
